[On the necessity of benefit assessments across all indications].

[Article in German]

Breyer F(1).

Author information:
(1)Universität Konstanz und DIW Berlin. Friedrich.Breyer@uni-konstanz.de

IQWiG's General Methods catalogue has raised a controversial debate among 
experts, and one of the major issues is the catalogue's authors' decision to 
exclusively use indication-specific output measures for benefit assessments. In 
contrast, numerous critics of this approach demand that benefit be measured 
using a uniform scale which is valid and interpretable for all indications, such 
as the "quality-adjusted life-year" (QALY). The present article will take a 
critical look at the arguments put forward by IQWiG and point out the 
disadvantages of purely indication-specific benefit assessments. We will then 
explore the legal possibilities of benefit assessments independent of the type 
of disease, and make some suggestions for the future approach to healthcare 
evaluation in Germany.

